The paper deals with designing node differentially private algorithms for graph statistics, which falls under the category of computer science and discrete mathematics. The paper specifically focuses on Lipschitz extensions for multi-dimensional functions on graphs, which suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the exponential mechanism, which is a tool used in information theory and machine learning, indicating that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper proposes new tools for designing differentially private algorithms, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper deals with data privacy, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). Finally, the paper deals with graph statistics, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
